\begin_layout Standard
Earth encounters are known to affect the properties of near-Earth objects
 (NEOs) through tidal effects.
 Binzel et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Binzel2010Nature"

\end_inset

 showed that weathered surfaces of asteroids are 'refreshed' upon an Earth
 encounter, causing less reddening to be observed than would otherwise be
 expected.
 Richardson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Richardson1998Icarus"

\end_inset

 conducted numerical simulations which showed that the tidal forces encountered
 by Earth-crossing asteroids may cause mass shifting and removal during
 a flyby, resulting changes such as in distortions, fragment trains, and
 orbiting ejecta.
 Rotation in particular was studied by Takihashi et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Takahashi2013AJ"

\end_inset

, who showed that there was a significant shift in rotational angular momentum
 during periodic flybys.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rotational period and asteroid shape are properties which may be extracted
 from a photometric light curve after a period of observation.
 The brightness of individual asteroids varies due to changes in heliocentric
 and geocentric distance, rotation, and solar phase angle 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Harris1989AsteroidsII"

\end_inset

.
 The changes due to distance are generally removed during data reduction
 by using a 'reduced magnitude' value, but the periodic changes in brightness
 due to rotation and phase angle yield important information regarding the
 dynamics of the asteroid.
 Along with other information, spin rates may tell us about the structure
 and collision history of an asteroid.
 Most smaller asteroids (0.15 km < D < 10 km) are thought to be 'rubble piles'
 held together by self-gravity, since a rate barrier appears to exist, beyond
 which small asteroids are not found to exceed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pravec2002AsteroidsIII"

\end_inset

.
 As spin states asymtotically approach rotation around the principal axis
 of maximum moment of inertia, asteroid light curves are expected to be
 at least double-peaked, with the exception of near-spherical or other degenerat
e cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This thesis extends on the work done on asteroidal Earth encounters described
 above by examining the effects of Earth encounters on asteroid rotational
 periods and amplitudes.
 To these effects, minimum orbit intersection distance (MOID) may be used
 as a measure how close an Earth encounter was.
 Instantaneous MOID may be determined from the present-day orbital parameters
 of an object, and will be used as a first-pass look at the relationship
 between encounters and period/amplitude.
 A more in-depth look may involve conducting a MOID calculation by integrating
 the orbit of a particular object back into the past to determine how gravitatio
nal perturbations may have changed the MOID to its present-day value.
 This thesis uses photometric and astrometric data from an ongoing asteroid
 survey to extract rotational periods, rotational amplitudes, and MOID for
 small (D < 1 km) NEOs.
\end_layout

